// C2: Acting Components
instance MotorGearTransmissionMechanism : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Primary actuation unit consisting of a permanent magnet synchronous motor and cycloidal gear transmission for high-precision motion control in the MABI MAX 100 industrial robot's first axis. Regulated through closed-loop feedback from position encoders with torque/force limits determined by mechanical design."
]

instance RoboticController : DTDFVocab:ActingComponent [
    base:desc "Dedicated controller managing physical actuators for robotic operations. Implements safety constraints through regulation of actuation range and prevention of over-actuation or mechanical failure via closed-loop feedback mechanisms."
]

// C3: Physical Sensing Components
instance AngularDisplacementEncoderFirstAxis : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "High-precision position encoder deployed on the first axis motor-gear transmission system to measure angular displacement for closed-loop control. Part of two-encoder configuration per drive with MQTT-based time-series data streaming."
    DTDFVocab:producedData AngularDisplacementDataFirstAxis
]

instance AngularDisplacementEncoderSecondAxis : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "High-precision position encoder deployed on the second axis motor-gear transmission system to measure angular displacement for closed-loop control. Part of two-encoder configuration per drive with MQTT-based time-series data streaming."
    DTDFVocab:producedData AngularDisplacementDataSecondAxis
]

// C4: Physical-to-Virtual Interaction
instance AngularDisplacementDataFirstAxis : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom AngularDisplacementEncoderFirstAxis
]

instance AngularDisplacementDataSecondAxis : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom AngularDisplacementEncoderSecondAxis
]

instance MotorTorqueData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom MotorGearTransmissionMechanism
]

instance AngularVelocityData : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom MotorGearTransmissionMechanism
]

// C10: Models/Data
instance GeometricModelFirstAxis : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "SysML Internal Block Diagram representation of the first axis motor-gear transmission system components and their interfaces for mechanical layout validation."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SysMLToolchain
]

instance BehavioralStateMachineModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "SysML v1.7 state machine model representing the robotic controller's operational states and transitions for closed-loop control validation."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SimulinkSimulation
]

instance FrictionModelExecutable : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "MathWorks MATLAB Simulink executable model simulating joint friction dynamics for the first axis to enable dynamic behavior analysis and closed-loop validation."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo SimulinkSimulation
]

instance AngularDisplacementDataProcessed : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Processed angular displacement data aggregated from MQTT streams, converted to floating-point values for analysis and visualization."
    DTDFVocab:fromData AngularDisplacementDataFirstAxis, AngularDisplacementDataSecondAxis
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataAggregationService
]

instance TorqueDataProcessed : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Processed motor torque data derived from transmission system measurements, used for mechanical analysis and control optimization."
    DTDFVocab:fromData MotorTorqueData
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataAggregationService
]

instance AngularVelocityDataProcessed : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Processed angular velocity data from motor-gear transmission, enabling dynamic behavior analysis and predictive modeling."
    DTDFVocab:fromData AngularVelocityData
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataAggregationService
]

// C11: Enablers
instance SysMLToolchain : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "IBM Rational Software Architect implementation of SysML for multi-layered modeling (requirements → logical architecture → physical layer) following RFLP methodology. Enables component-connector modeling and interface definition."
    DTDFVocab:enables DigitalShadowDataAggregation, ModelValidationService
]

instance SimulinkSimulation : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "MathWorks MATLAB Simulink environment for executing friction models and validating closed-loop control behavior through dynamic system simulation."
    DTDFVocab:enables ControlValidationService, DynamicBehaviorAnalysis
]

instance MQTTDataStreaming : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "MQTT-based publish-subscribe protocol implementation for low-latency, high-throughput transmission of time-series sensor data from physical components to digital representations."
    DTDFVocab:enables DataAggregationService, RealTimeMonitoring
]

instance HeterogeneousDatabaseLayer : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Aggregation framework for contextual data traces including relational and time-series databases, enabling structured storage of processed sensor data for analytics."
    DTDFVocab:enables BaselineMonitoringService
]

// C6: Services
instance DigitalShadowDataAggregation : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Passive one-way data aggregation service collecting contextual data traces (torque, angular displacement, velocity) from physical robot components via automated sensors for real-time abstraction."
    DTDFVocab:provides BaselineMonitoringInsight
]

instance ControlValidationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Simulation-based service validating closed-loop control behavior using executable friction models and state machine representations to ensure system accuracy."
    DTDFVocab:provides ControlAccuracyInsight
]

instance DynamicBehaviorAnalysis : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Multi-physics analysis service identifying joint friction characteristics and dynamic behavior patterns from processed sensor data for optimization recommendations."
    DTDFVocab:provides OptimizationRecommendationAction
]

instance BaselineMonitoringService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Passive state tracking service monitoring operational parameters (mechanical wear, energy consumption) without autonomous intervention for post-hoc analysis."
    DTDFVocab:provides MechanicalWearInsight
]

instance RealTimeMonitoring : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Low-latency monitoring service providing continuous feedback on system parameters through MQTT-based data streams for immediate visualization."
    DTDFVocab:provides RealTimeVisualizationAction
]

instance ModelValidationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service for validating SysML models against requirements and logical architecture constraints."
    DTDFVocab:provides ModelValidationInsight
]

instance DataAggregationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service for aggregating and preprocessing raw sensor data into structured formats for analysis."
    DTDFVocab:provides ContextualDataEnrichment
]

// C17: Insights/Actions
instance BaselineMonitoringInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Aggregated contextual data traces serving as baseline for future Digital Twin development and enabling post-hoc analysis of physical system behavior."
]

instance ControlAccuracyInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Simulation-driven insights validating closed-loop control accuracy through friction modeling and state machine validation."
]

instance OptimizationRecommendationAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Automated recommendations for improving control accuracy based on dynamic behavior analysis and friction modeling results."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance MechanicalWearInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Passive tracking of mechanical wear patterns and energy consumption metrics for predictive maintenance analysis."
]

instance ContextualDataEnrichment : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Insights derived from enriched contextual data enabling higher-level analytics and Digital Twin development."
]

instance ModelValidationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Validation results confirming SysML models meet architectural and functional requirements."
]

instance RealTimeVisualizationAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Dashboard-based visualization of real-time system parameters for stakeholder interaction and immediate decision support."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic false
]

// C1: Environment
instance ManufacturingAutomationEnvironment : DTDFVocab:Environment [
    base:contains RoboticController, MotorGearTransmissionMechanism, AngularDisplacementEncoderFirstAxis, AngularDisplacementEncoderSecondAxis
]

// C5: Components
instance FirstAxisDriveSystem : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Primary drive system consisting of permanent magnet synchronous motor and cycloidal gear transmission for the MABI MAX 100's first axis, enabling high-precision positioning in manufacturing automation."
    base:isContainedIn ManufacturingAutomationEnvironment
]

instance SecondAxisDriveSystem : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Secondary drive system mirroring the first axis configuration with independent motor-gear transmission for multi-axis motion control."
    base:isContainedIn ManufacturingAutomationEnvironment
]

instance MABIMAX100Robot : DTDFVocab:Component [
    base:desc "Serial kinematic industrial robot (MABI MAX 100) with first and second axis drive systems designed for high-precision machining applications."
    base:contains FirstAxisDriveSystem, SecondAxisDriveSystem
    base:isContainedIn ManufacturingAutomationEnvironment
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system described in the provided documents does not explicitly detail synchronization frequencies, time scales for services, latency requirements, or temporal granularity needs. However, the context implies that **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** methodologies (e.g., SysML, ADLs like AADL, or simulation tools such as MathWorks Simulink) are used to model system behavior, which inherently requires precise temporal alignment between physical and digital components. For example, **SysML state machines** or **MontiArc Automaton** may enforce discrete or continuous time scales depending on the application domain. The documents do not specify exact frequencies (e.g., Hz, ms, or seconds) or latency constraints, but the integration of **simulation tools** (e.g., Simulink) suggests real-time or near-real-time synchronization is assumed for dynamic system behaviors. No concrete temporal metrics (e.g., <100ms latency) are provided, thus leaving this aspect abstracted to domain-specific implementations."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system’s orchestration is framed within **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** paradigms, leveraging **architecture patterns** from ADLs (e.g., **component-connector models** in ACME or AADL) and **behavioral modeling** (e.g., state machines in SysML v1.7 or MontiArc Automaton). The **component integration** is achieved through **heterogeneous toolchains**, combining ADLs with simulation tools (e.g., Simulink) or general-purpose languages (e.g., C++, Java). **Resource management** is implied via **modular decomposition** (e.g., RFLP layers), where each layer (requirements, functions, logic, physics) abstracts responsibilities. **System-wide coordination** is not explicitly detailed but is inferred from the **integration of multiple modeling notations** (e.g., SysML for architecture + Simulink for dynamics), suggesting a **hybrid orchestration** approach. The document does not specify **real-time coordination protocols** (e.g., DDS, ROS) or **cloud-edge deployment strategies**, leaving these aspects to domain-specific implementations."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "
The lifecycle of a Digital Twin (DT) system is structured through **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** methodologies, encompassing multiple abstraction layers: **requirements, functional architecture, logical architecture, and product/technical layers**. These stages are governed by methodologies such as **RFLP (Requirements, Functions, Logics, Physics)**, **OOSEM**, **SPES**, or **SMArDT**, which systematically decompose system complexity. The lifecycle transitions between phases involve **architecture description languages (ADLs)** like **ACME, AADL, MontiArc, or SysML Internal Block Diagrams (IBDs)** to model components, interfaces, connectors, and composition. Behavior modeling integrates **state machines (SysML v1.7)** or **MontiArc Automaton**, while detailed behavior is further refined using **MathWorks Simulink, simulation tools, or general-purpose languages (C++, Java)**. Lifecycle governance ensures integration of **heterogeneous stakeholder perspectives** and **modeling notations** across tools, emphasizing **version control, traceability, and iterative refinement** to maintain consistency and accuracy throughout development, deployment, and operational phases.
"
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin’s **model fidelity** is validated through **comparative analysis of simulated vs. measured data**, where deviations are analyzed to assess accuracy. **Uncertainty quantification** is implicitly addressed via the **sensor arrangement** (dual encoders) to reduce **backlash and positional uncertainty**, though explicit error metrics (e.g., RMSE, confidence intervals) are not provided. **Quality assurance processes** are inferred from **MBSE methodologies**, including **SysML-based verification** and **Simulink-driven validation**, though no formalized error detection/correction mechanisms (e.g., Kalman filters, machine learning-based anomaly detection) are documented. The system relies on **control-loop feedback** (e.g., via SINUMERIK 840D sl) for runtime fidelity adjustments, but **no explicit validation protocols** (e.g., ISO/IEC standards, certification frameworks) are referenced."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The **technical network infrastructure** for this Digital Twin system is not explicitly detailed in the provided documents. However, the **MQTT protocol** is mentioned as a means for streaming data from physical to digital components, implying it may also be used for communication between system components. No further specifications regarding network topology (e.g., mesh, star), bandwidth requirements, latency constraints, redundancy mechanisms, or security protocols (e.g., TLS, VPN) are provided."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The deployment infrastructure for this Digital Twin system is grounded in **Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE)** methodologies, which utilize **architecture description languages (ADLs)** like SysML for defining system components, interfaces, and interconnections. The system may leverage **heterogeneous tools** (e.g., MathWorks Simulink for behavior modeling, general-purpose languages like C++ or Java for implementation) to ensure interoperability. However, specific deployment platforms (cloud/edge/on-premise), computational/storage requirements, scalability mechanisms, or availability assurances (e.g., redundancy, failover) are **not in Document**. The system must accommodate **multiple abstraction layers** (requirements, functional/logical architecture, physical layer) as per MBSE practices, but no explicit hosting environment (e.g., containerization, orchestration) is referenced."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin system integrates with **external systems via MQTT-based streaming protocols** for real-time sensor data acquisition, as explicitly stated in the context: *'We have access to time series of all sensors, which are streamed via MQTT.'* Horizontal integration adheres to **enterprise interoperability standards** implied by MBSE methodologies, though no specific protocols (e.g., OPC UA, REST APIs) or **enterprise service buses (ESB)** are mentioned beyond MQTT for sensor data. The system integrates with **heterogeneous stakeholders and perspectives** (e.g., requirements, functional, and physical layers) via **MBSE toolchains** (e.g., SysML, Simulink), ensuring **cross-domain compatibility**. **No explicit integration patterns** (e.g., API gateways, event-driven architectures) are documented, but the **MQTT-based data flow** and **ADL toolchains** facilitate **plug-and-play interoperability** with external systems. Dependencies on external systems are limited to **sensor data ingestion** and **simulation tool compatibility** (e.g., Simulink models)."
]

instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "
The Digital Twin system incorporates **safety cell restrictions** to ensure operational safety, where the **safety cell of the robot** (as referenced in [44]) explicitly restricts the **maximum working range** to predefined boundaries, mitigating collision risks. The system leverages **MQTT protocol** ([52]) for communication, which inherently supports **QoS (Quality of Service) levels** (0, 1, 2) to prioritize critical safety-related data transmissions, ensuring timely response to emergency conditions. While no explicit **access control mechanisms** or **authentication systems** are detailed in the provided documents, the **Digital Shadow methodology** ([42]) implies a structured data flow where **conformance relations** ([41]) could theoretically enforce role-based access control (RBAC) for sensitive operations. However, **no formal threat mitigation strategies**, **fail-safe mechanisms**, or **risk assessment frameworks** (e.g., IEC 62443) are explicitly described in the context of the Digital Twin system. The **Asset Administration Shell (AAS)** ([46], [47], [50])—though referenced in broader Industry 4.0 contexts—is not directly tied to safety-critical system considerations in the provided documents. The **functional mockup interface (FMI)** ([51]) for simulation models does not address security or safety but ensures **interoperability** between tools, which could indirectly support safety validation workflows. Overall, the documents emphasize **operational safety boundaries** (e.g., robot safety cells) and **communication protocols** (e.g., MQTT QoS) but lack detailed **cybersecurity protocols**, **fail-safe designs**, or **compliance frameworks** for safety-critical systems."
]